24:20.880 --> 24:28.000
Policy at the National Security Council. Mr. Wolfowitz, considered a leader of the neo-conservatives,

24:28.000 --> 24:33.200
has an informative history prior to his being appointed as Deputy Secretary of Defense.

24:34.400 --> 24:39.040
Joseph Cerencioni wrote for the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace just

24:39.040 --> 24:43.680
one day before the US would invade Iraq on 19 March 2003.

24:45.120 --> 24:49.760
Long before September 11, before the first inspections in Iraq had started,

24:49.760 --> 24:55.120
a small group of influential officials and experts in Washington were calling for regime change in

24:55.120 --> 25:02.480
Iraq. Some never wanted to end the 1991 war. Many are now administration officials. Their

25:02.480 --> 25:08.240
organization, dedication, and brilliance offer much to admire, even for those who disagree with

25:08.240 --> 25:15.600
the policies they advocate. Cerencioni's history begins as early as 1992. Paul Wolfowitz, then

25:15.600 --> 25:20.720
Under Secretary of Defense for Policy, supervised the drafting of the Defense Policy Guidance

25:20.720 --> 25:26.000
document. A partially redacted version of the document is available in the National Security

25:26.000 --> 25:32.560
Archive. A section titled Middle East and Southwest Asia reads, As demonstrated by Iraq's invasion

25:32.560 --> 25:38.320
of Kuwait, it remains fundamentally important to prevent a hegemon or alignment of powers from

25:38.320 --> 25:44.720
dominating the region. We must endeavor to curb proliferation of nuclear, chemical, and biological

25:44.720 --> 25:50.640
weapons, as well as ballistic and cruise missiles. The infusion of new and improved conventional

25:50.640 --> 25:55.760
arms and the proliferation of ballistic missiles and weapons of mass destruction during the past

25:55.760 --> 26:01.280
decade have dramatically increased offensive capabilities and the risk of future wars throughout

26:01.280 --> 26:07.280
the region. Excerpts from the document were subsequently leaked to the New York Times,

26:07.280 --> 26:13.120
which caused something of a scandal. Embarrassed, the first Bush administration retracted it.

26:13.200 --> 26:18.480
Its drafting had been supervised by Paul D. Wolfowitz, the Pentagon's Under Secretary for

26:18.480 --> 26:23.680
Policy, wrote Patrick Tyler, who goes on to explain the strong emphasis elsewhere in the

26:23.680 --> 26:29.680
document and in other Pentagon planning on using military force if necessary to prevent

26:29.680 --> 26:34.880
the proliferation of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction in such countries as

26:34.880 --> 26:39.760
North Korea, Iraq, some of the successor republics to the Soviet Union, and in Europe.

26:40.720 --> 26:46.000
Though it was retracted, its supervisor of course became Deputy Secretary of Defense,

26:46.000 --> 26:53.120
